## 7. The conversation requirements, answered explicitly

The brief asks for four points to be addressed on stage. Prepare one slide and one call clip for each.

**Who is the agent speaking for.** Opening line, always, unprompted:
> "Guten Tag, mein Name ist Alex, ich bin ein KI-Assistent und hole im Auftrag von Architekturbüro Vetrov Angebote für ein Sanierungsprojekt in Dresden ein. Haben Sie zwei Minuten?"

If asked "Bin ich mit einem Roboter verbunden?" the answer is short, honest, and moves on without apologising:
> "Ja, ich bin ein KI-Assistent, ich rufe im Auftrag eines Kunden an. Wenn Sie lieber direkt mit ihm sprechen, verbinde ich gerne. Ansonsten: haben Sie die Kapazität für ein Projekt im September?"

Note for the German market: this is not just good manners. The EU AI Act transparency obligation (Art. 50) requires that people know they are interacting with an AI. Put that on the slide, it separates you from teams that treat disclosure as a UX detail.

**How it survives friction.** Build and demo: interruption handling (barge-in), the "Ich bin auf der Baustelle, rufen Sie später an" deflection converted into a scheduled callback with a concrete time, the receptionist gatekeeper, and the outright hangup logged as a structured decline. Latency target under 700 ms to first token, because a pause on a construction site phone call reads as a bad connection and gets you hung up on.

**Where the honesty line sits.** Hard constraints, implemented as tool-level validation and stated on a slide:
- The agent may only cite a competing quote that exists in the collected quote store, with a call ID and a transcript timestamp
- The agent may never invent scope, quantities, volume or urgency
- The agent may never claim to be a human
- The agent may never promise an order it is not authorised to place
Implementation detail worth showing: the leverage string is not generated by the LLM, it is templated from a verified record. The model chooses when to use leverage, not what the leverage says.

**How every call ends.** Three permitted terminal states, nothing else: itemised quote captured, callback commitment with a date and time, or documented decline with a reason. The report shows the terminal state for every call including the failures. Showing your failures is explicitly rewarded by the brief.

